 (3,1,'2009-11-17 14:02:22','2009-11-17 14:02:22','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\r\n\r\nHere\'s what I did:\r\n\r\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\r\n\r\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Wordpress in a lunch break','','publish','open','open','','wordpress-in-a-lunch-break','','','2009-11-17 14:03:04','2009-11-17 14:03:04','',0,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/?p=3',0,'post','',0),
 (4,1,'2009-11-17 14:01:40','2009-11-17 14:01:40','I\'ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title=\"Wordpress installation instructions\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install\" target=\"_blank\">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.\n\nHere\'s what I did:\n\nInstalled PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)\n<ul>\n	<li><a title=\"PHP documentation\" href=\"http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php\" target=\"_blank\">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\n	<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\n	<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title=\"MySQL Downloads\" href=\"http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/\" target=\"_blank\">the MySQL site</a></li>\n	<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\n	<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title=\"wp-config.php settings\" href=\"http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php\" target=\"_blank\"> to point to your database</a></li>\n	<li>Browse to the installation page and it\'s as easy as that</li>\n</ul>\nNext, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.\n\nI did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.','Lunch break Wordpressing','','inherit','open','open','','3-revision','','','2009-11-17 14:01:40','2009-11-17 14:01:40','',3,'http://blog.jonathansewell.co.uk.temp.realssl.com/index.php/2009/11/17/3-revision/',0,'revision','',0),
